Embedding project templates in Visual Studio Code extension using Yeoman for templating. (#515)

This change is modifying the approach followed by the VS Code extension for Q# to create projects of the following types:

- Standalone console application
- Quantum library
- Unit testing project

Instead of relying on the command line templates that can be maintained outside of the VSCode extension, this change embeds a version-matching copy of the templates, so new projects can be created independently of the dotnet new templates.

Use glpk-4.65, which is thread-safe

Initial placement in the mapper uses lemon/mip.
Lemon/mip can use various underlying solvers among which glpk.
Glpk and glpk-devel were installed in the system to allow its use.
However, these are old versions, not thread-safe.
A new one glpk-4.65 was reported to be thread-safe,
i.e. working with the timeout solution of the call to the solver of glpk
that works with a separate thread that does the solve and a main thread
that either timeouts or earlier is awoken by the subthread with a result.
In order to install this glpk-4.65 the following was done:
- uninstall the old glpk glpk-devel
- make sure to use the "scl enable devtoolset-6 bash" for the right compilers
    Because swig (the tool to create Python/C++ interfaces) cannot work with older compilers.
    Also because compiling with older compilers failed below in make.
- downloaded glpk into a place outside /home to allow sudo do its work
- ./configure --prefix=/usr --libdir=/usr/lib64
    Because OpenQL somehow doesn't search in /usr/local (default for glpk install)
    so use /usr as prefix so that /usr/include is used instead of /usr/local/include.
    Override then /usr/lib to be /usr/lib64 because we are using x64.
- make
    Makes everything locally in the download environment
- make check
    Was ok, ran a simple mip
- sudo make install
    Sudo because /usr and /usr/lib64 are not accessible for an ordinary user.
    Install uses the comfigured paths above.
        /usr/lib64/libglpk.a etc.
        /usr/include/glpk.h
        /usr/bin/glpsol etc.
- the downloaded environment can be deleted because installation was successfull
- update the top CMakelists.txt to use /usr/local/include in the include path:
        SET(CLI11_INCLUDE_DIRS
          "${CMAKE_SOURCE_DIR}/deps/CLI11/include"
            "/usr/local/include"
            )
- please note that earlier the CMake env of lemon was modified to create
  an ordinary library instead of a shared library to be able to have glpk in;
  glpk doesn't want a shared library
- cd cbuild ; cmake .. ; make

Mapping reports (both kernel-specific and totals) moved from end of qasm files to separate report files.

Mapping reports were generated as part of writing qasm, as comment at end of qasm files.
This required code and extensions to classes such as kernel.h and program.h specific for this reporting.
To avoid such extension, reporting and qasm file generation were decoupled.
Reporting was moved to and is now supported by a separate group of functions in src/report.h.
All related class extensions were deleted.

Reporting statistics can be done per kernel and over all kernels.
It is open in the sense that additional reporting with pass-specific information is supported.
Reporting statistics is enabled by the option: write_report_files which is "no" by default.
Reporting qasm files (before and after passes) listens to the write_qasm_files option.
Both arch/cc_light/cc_light_eqasm_compiler.h and arch/quantumsim_eqasm_compiler.h were updated.

Quantum operands in gate.operands, classical operands in gate.creg_operands, etc.

Classical operands were for most of the gates stored in gate.operands.
This led to problems in correct dependence analysis in the scheduler
and in correctly creating qasm for gates.
Before this change, several tests surprisingly didn't pass.
But after this pass, also several tests didn't pass anymore.
So also some of these passes were corrected,
e.g. to cater for the use of r28 in computing condition code which
requires the number of classical registers to be at least 29.
Still several tests don't pass, and this has to be analyzed.
Most problematic are the classical_cc gates that are put in a circuit
and subsequently a scheduler or a mapper has to cope with:
e.g. imagine an fmr that is unknown to the scheduler and for which
the dependencies have to be determined in the depgraph computation of the scheduler.
Possibly, the golden outputs have to be updated.

So, this commit is not done because the branch is consistent and fault-less.

Furthermore, as most user visible change, the interface to quantumsim has changed.
Quantumsim is not enabled by passing a quantum.json file as config file.
Instead, one uses any json file that is for a target that one wants to simulate,
and sets the "quantumsim" option to "no", "yes", or "qsoverlay";
the "yes" enables the usual quantumsim output, the "qsoverlay" for the qsoverlay version of quantumsim.
And furthermore, two outputs are produced, one after the prescheduler
and one just before writing the qisa file in cc_light.

Added timeout support for initial placement, and then stop or skip/continue

Initialplace option values are: no,yes,1s,10s,1m,10m,1h,1sx,10sx,1mx,10mx,1hx
On no: don't try it and just use mapping that was used before, and do the heuristic map/route.
On yes: take all time needed (infinite timeout)
On 1s,10s,1m,10m,1h time out after 1s, 10s, 1m, 10m, 1h, respectively and continue compilation
without an initial placement, i.e. in the mapping that was used before it was tried, and do the heuristic map/route.
On 1sx,10sx,1mx,10mx,1hx time out after 1s, 10s, 1m, 10m, 1h, respectively and stop compilation.

Option maptiebreak(first,last,random) applies to all strategies (mapper options: base, minextend,minextendrc)

Option maptiebreak decides choice from equally well paths: first, last or random choice
Option mapper (base, minextend, minextendrc) decides strategy to value paths.
Now also base generates all shortest paths and applies maptiebreak to choose from all these.
And minextend[rc] generates all least extending paths and chooses as maptiebreak prescribes, instead of the first from the set.
Furthermore, the random generator is seeded from a microsecond timer to make subsequent runs use different random choices.

Deep-critical path scheduling (ASAP and ALAP) working.

The commutativity support in the dependence graph unleashed a lot of freedom to the scheduler:
it has more options to choose from (all in its avlist) and more of them are critical (delaying one would delay the circuit).
So just comparing two options for the amount of criticality is not sufficient anymore:
also the criticality of the depending nodes and even the whole critical depending dependence subgraph behind each matters.
This criticality comparison for selecting the best option to schedule next has been extended to look deep forward.
This was done by keeping the avlist in deep-critical order, highest deep-critical node first.

cc_light resource manager extended to support backward resource management, e.g. in combination with ALAP (backward compatible change)

The cc_light resource manager has been extended with backward resource management next to forward resource management.
This supports ALAP_rc scheduling next to ASAP_rc scheduling as until now.
Furthermore, the resource manager was extended with the new resource detuned_qubits.
And the resource manager was extended with several constructors and an improved destructor.
A new .cc test series was added and an accompanying .json file (with the new resource constraint).

This change to the resource manager is backward compatible.
The old use and old constructor creates a forward scheduling resource manager.

In OpenQL's ir, kernel.c is the only construct that contains gates; kernel.bundles has been deleted.

Kernel.c and kernel.bundles were alternative structures to represent the circuit.
Now, kernel.c is the only one.
Where necessary locally in passes, bundler() creates bundles from a circuit and circuiter() creates circuit from bundles.
Whether bundles can be created, depends on kernel.cycles_valid.
This bool state value is set to false everywhere where a gate is added to or deleted from or moved in a circuit.
It is set to true everywhere where the circuit has been scheduled (so that the cycle attribute got valid,
and the circuit's gates have been sorted in non-decreating order of their cycle attribute).

Where necessary, code was moved/reorganized to make this possible.
The resulting implementation is fully backward compatible.

Some renaming was done to variables to make clear that they don't contain bundles.

Added deterministic path selection, following only borders instead of all shortest paths

New option: mappathselect with values all or borders, default all.
This is orthogonal to mapper option and maptiebreak option:
with mappathselect==borders at most 2 src to tgt paths are selected
(and all split variations are then generated from them),
while mappathselect==all selects all possible shortest paths from src to tgt
(after which then all split variations are generated).
Subsequently, these generated paths are subjected to the heuristic (mapper option).
When the heuristic has more than 1 outcome (e.g. equal circuit extension in case of minextend[rc]),
then maptiebreak decides which of the final equal results to take.

Print kernel statistic 'qubit cycles use', for each qubit the sum of the number of cycles it was busy executing gates

Each qubit cycles use value, when divided by Depth, gives a 0<=value<=1, giving fraction of cycles qubit was not idling.
When summed and divided by the number of used qubits, gives a measure of the parallelism of the circuit, 1==full.
This measure indicates how well the chain of circuit, mapper, and scheduler are performing.
Also when reading this value after each pass, and dividing the value after by before, it gives a measure for the pass.

An addition option mapselectmaxswaps was added to maximize
the number of swaps inserted when selecting an alternative.
This means that the target CNOT may not get NN when this max is set to 1.
And that not all swaps are added in one go for one target CNOT,
but that for a set of CNOTs, distributed over these, gradually single swaps are added,
with the idea that they interfer and give a better result in total.
Note that this requires that maplookahead is set to "all".
Perhaps we need to extend the latter option with a value, e.g. to select the most critical 2.

WIP on setup.py (commit prior to big revert)

The situation with setuptools managing extension builds seems to
be that

 - setuptools' SWIG build is broken, requiring janky workarounds to
   sort of work (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/12491328),
   and by default it just spams SWIG's build artifacts in the source
   directory. Nice(!)
 - linking the setuptools-built module against shared libraries
   generated by CMake is broken on Linux/Mac because CMake has to know
   where the files are going to end up on the system in order to set
   R(UN)PATH correctly, which is impossible for a distributed module,
   because people might install Python modules anywhere. This cannot be
   worked around at runtime by setting LD_LIBRARY_PATH from the loader
   script as I had hoped, because the environment variables as far as
   the runtime linker are concerned are fixed as soon as the Python
   executable is launched. This is only a problem because OpenQL
   consists of multiple libraries referencing each other (lemon and
   libqasm), but let's be honest, that really shouldn't be causing
   this much drama.
 - linking the setuptools-built module against *static* libraries
   generated by CMake is broken in general, because static libraries
   can't handle transitive dependencies. They'd have to be hardcoded
   into setup.py, but LEMON's dependency on glpk etc. is figured out by
   CMake at configure-time and thus cannot be hardcoded. Turns out that
   it's virtually impossible to pull this list out of CMake
   (https://gitlab.kitware.com/cmake/cmake/-/issues/12435), so this is a
   dead end. Also, it shouldn't even be possible to link static objects
   together into the shared object that Python needs, but that's what

Updated tests after remove CBox & add modularity

The configuration file for some of the tests needed to be updated
after the removal of the CBox backend. Furthermore, with the addition
of modularity some of the tests were failing in CI due to wrong options
being propagated from one unit test to another. Therefore, a reset_options
function has been added to the compiler that require now each unit test to call
explicitly the selfSetUp function to set its required options.

Added unique_output option to make output qasm/report files unique on creation

The new option has value "no" or "yes", default "no".
When set, each output qasm/report file with a name derived from the
program name is made unique by appending a version number to its name.
To this end, a file with name <test_output_dir>/<program_name>.unique
is maintained that contains the version number of the last run.
It is created when not there.

Change the name of the generated quantumsim scripts.

Reversed the order of test_file_name + _quantumsim_ to quantumsim_ + test_file_name
to avoid generated quantumsim scripts being included in compiler regression tests.
Failing to do so will crash any subsequent compiler tests if quantumsim
is not available as a module on the system.
